SIMPLE: slaughter
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slaughter
<hw>Slaugh"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>slautir</ets>, <ets>slaughter</ets>, <ets>slaghter</ets>, Icel.
<ets>sl⟦amac⟧tr</ets> slain flesh, modified by OE. <ets>slaught</ets>,
<ets>slaht</ets>, slaughter, fr. AS. <ets>sleaht</ets> a stroke, blow;
both from the root of E. slay. See <er>Slay</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, and
cf. <er>Onslaught</er>.]</ety> <def>The act of killing.</def>
Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The extensive, violent, bloody, or
wanton destruction of life; carnage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On war and mutual <qex>slaughter</qex> bent.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The act of killing cattle or other beasts for
market.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Carnage; massacre; butchery; murder;
havoc.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slaughter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slaughter
<hw>Slaugh"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Slaughtered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Slaughtering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To visit with
great destruction of life; to kill; to slay in battle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your castle is surprised; your wife and babes⟦br⟧
Savagely <qex>slaughtered</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To butcher; to kill for the market, as
beasts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slaughterer</ent>⟦br⟧
